# Git author identity (trhlow)

Before creating commits or pushing to GitHub in this repository, verify Git identity matches:

- `user.name` must be `trhlow`
- `user.email` must be `thlong190705@gmail.com`

## What to do

1) Check current values:

```powershell
git config user.name
git config user.email
git config --global user.name
git config --global user.email
```

2) If any value differs, set global identity (preferred):

```powershell
git config --global user.name "trhlow"
git config --global user.email "thlong190705@gmail.com"
```

3) If the repo has local overrides, fix them too:

```powershell
git config user.name "trhlow"
git config user.email "thlong190705@gmail.com"
```

## Notes

- `user.name` / `user.email` affect commit metadata (author/committer), not GitHub authentication.
- If rewriting history, ensure rewritten commits use the correct author/committer before force pushing.
